\begin_layout Section
Road Map to understanding how lasers work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We will look at Rabi oscillations and how a coherent wave is resonant with
 a 2-level system.
 Specifically, we will investigate the power flow between the atom and the
 field and we will determine the conditions needed for sustained amplification
 of the input field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then, we will introduce damping (and the related concept of susceptibility)
 into the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We will study rate equations which will combine all of the concepts studied
 in the previous points and will help us determine when laser action is
 possible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Simple Semi-Classical treatment of the laser
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter presents the most simple treatment of the laser, and will make
 use of the following 
\emph on
assumptions
\emph default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Approximate the atom as a 2-level system.
 The first level is an s-wave (ground state) and the second is a p-wave
 (first excited state).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The atom is isolated (i.e.
 no damping), so will assume that the atom is alone and it is not interacting
 with other radiation modes than the input field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The rotating wave approximation (RWA) which will help us treat the interaction
 of the electron with the field analytically.
 Specifically, we will find that the interaction term in the Hamiltonian
 is time-dependent and we will assume that the original eigenbasis of the
 system stays relevant (so the eigenbasis changes adiabatically - i.e.
 slowly in time).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Two-level systems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Description
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 2 level system is modeled in the following way: 
