2 level system interacting with an incoming field
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 The energy difference between the two levels will be denoted by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hbar\Omega\equiv E_{2}-E_{1}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Heuristic justification of the 2 level atom assumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In reality, atoms contain many more energy states than just 2 states.
 However, many of the energy states play no role in the interaction of the
 electron with the field as only a few states can satisfy the conservation
 of energy condition.
 Moreover, transitions that satisfy the resonance condition dominate the
 dynamics.
 Note though that for a very strong field, this statement breaks down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hamiltonian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The system is modeled with the following Hamiltonian
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
H=H_{0}-\vec{\mu}.\vec{\mathcal{E}}\left(\vec{x},\vec{t}\right),\label{eq:test}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}$
\end_inset

 is is the Hamiltonian of the system, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\mu}=q\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 is the atomic dipole moment operator with electron charge 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\mathcal{E}}\left(\vec{x},\vec{t}\right)=\mbox{re}\left[\vec{E}\left(\vec{x},\vec{t}\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{E}=\vec{E}_{0}\exp\left[i\left(\vec{k}.\vec{r}-\omega t\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 being the electric field shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:aph190 2 level system"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

